Prologue
“I beseech you!” pleaded Queen Eirwen, “do not send her away! She is still a child!” The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. As he thought of this, his gaze darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue strands. In the Ice King's eyes, a girl meant weakness. After all, he had only produced sons up until this point.
“You have two choices: either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. This is his punishment for your failure, Eirwen.” He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did that.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Previously, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. The North was the non-magical kingdom, while the South was a realm filled with fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed, and there was an endless war between the two kingdoms until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
The despair in the south was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as a queen to the north, where she should bear a son, the future king. In this case, the north would unite with the south into one kingdom. The north accepted the proposal, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
“I beg you, my king, do to me what you will, lock me up, banish me, or kill me, but spare my child,” pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his queen with disgust. Maybe, just maybe, he might show her mercy. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him through his worst times and given him sons.
“Well then. The child can stay in the palace,” he said, which was acknowledged by the queen with a sigh. “But,” he added, “you will be executed.”
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she lowered her gaze to the ground. “Yes, my king.” She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the daughter of the queen to one of Eirwen's free rooms. Then, he commanded the guards to take Eirwen to the execution site, where all the citizens of the city could watch.
As the guards escorted her to the execution site, there was a loud commotion among the citizens, as they realized that their only beloved queen was going to be executed. Some people cried, others shouted and attacked the guards. Others wondered why this was happening, but everyone agreed.
"Let her go!"
"Why are you doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared—the executioner. The woman who was still queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the worst thing one could do to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then the executioner lit the wooden stake on fire, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Don't give up, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's regency.
Silence in the palace
Only a knock could be heard from the room located all the way at the left corner of the ever-cold palace in the south wing. The servants passing by always wondered what was in that room. They were afraid of it. Rumors circulated among the maids in the palace. Supposedly, the late wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room waiting to be let out.
Her guess could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory as she headed towards the south wing, while the servants circulated and whispered to each other. They had no idea what lay behind the door.
The rumors also concerned Ivory, as she was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" Ivory whispered before the door decorated with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if, unlike the last attempt, entry would actually be granted. I still have blue spots from the last time, she thought with a chuckle. Kari had thrown a book at Ivory's shoulder but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock came from inside, likely to say that she was there. Where else could she be?
"May I enter?" asked Ivory. Previously, Ivory had gone in without asking.
From inside, Ivory heard knocking. This likely meant a "yes." The cold and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a knock from what was supposedly an empty room, even though Ivory had been entering it for several years.
"I'll come in," said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people but not unexpected for her. Papers were scattered everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay around. There were no windows and very little to no light. Moreover, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said something). The room looked as if a snowstorm had swept through it.
The girl was curled up in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, and reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook is this?" asked Ivory and sat down next to Kari on the bed.
